      <scopecontent id="aspace_9b336e2399bf078ff1a1b2ca3649d73b">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection contains photographs of the 1964 Freddy Fixer parade and spectators in the Dixwell neighborhood of New Haven, CT taken by Paul Ganster, then an undergraduate student at Yale University. Contains silver gelatin photographic prints, contact sheets, safety film negatives, and born digital material. Contains creator supplied numbering system for photographic materials, see printed image inventory [Box 1, Folder 1] for more information.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_33ec58c4caf2af60207b10a864d94909">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Freddy Fixer parade is the oldest and longest running Black American parade in the Northeast of the United States since 1962. The parade originally began as a community run cleanup project in the Dixwell neighborhood of New Haven, CT, organized by Dr. Fred "Freddy Fixer" Smith and the Dixwell Development Agency, with the clean-up concluding with a meal. Early iterations of the parade included pageants and contests for children in the neighborhood to participate in, with most festivities happening at or near the Dixwell Community House. The parade continues to run to this day.</p>
         <p>Information in this historical note was primarily drawn from the Elm City Freddy Fixer Parade website, as well as from the Edward Grant Oral History Project, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_352cf8e40a6e20ecf8f4a00637a4c29b">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of Paul Ganster (Yale, 1965), 2024.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <prefercite id="aspace_22114065d7eb739727e1ed3b5af383e0">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Paul Ganster collection of Freddy Fixer Parade photographs. General Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_5659812e7aa5cc4ee729852720a047a5">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>These materials have been arranged and described according to national and local standards.  For more information, please refer to the Yale Archival Processing Manual.</p>
      </processinfo>
      <arrangement id="aspace_e145b1a0063461febe7c1e98c5eec674">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is organized by physical and digital photographic format.</p>
         <p>The original structure and file names of digital images have been maintained.</p>
      </arrangement>
